The Times has obtained tax-return data for President Trump extending over more than two decades. It tells a story fundamentally different from the one he’s sold to the public.Mr. Trump’s finances are under stress, beset by hundreds of millions in debt coming due and an I.R.S. audit that could cost him over $100 million.He paid $750 in federal income taxes in 2016, and nothing at all in 10 of the prior 15 years — largely because he lost so much money.
Tax records provide a detailed history of President Trump’s business career.
Here are the key findings of our investigation.
Read a note from Dean Baquet, our executive editor, about why we published this story.
